fu.util

Class FloatArrayList

  • java.lang.Object
    • fu.util.FloatArrayList

  • public class FloatArrayList
extends java.lang.Object
    In principle, an ArrayList<Float>, but it is much more memory efficient. The Float values are stored into float[], thus mainly the values are stored and not the references to Float objects. Thus, many million values can be stored withouth dealing with memory effects. Some differences to ArrayList<Float>
    • it cannot store null values
    • it is not a subclass of AbstractList
    • some methods are not implemented, e.g. removeAll, iterator
    • some methods exist beyond the ArrayList, e.g. max, min, sort
    • no range checks in the borders of the current array capacity
